img_description:
One of the most beautiful scenes my eyes have witnessed: sunrise over the Tiberias Lake. I will surely never forget the feeling of cold breeze and warm water on my feet. I will never forget the feeling of nostalgia. That something from our lives is truly missing. 
When all you think about is how many people died for this land, how many people faced homelessness and war for it, how much history the rocks have witnessed, it becomes unfathomable that this land is gone. 
من أجمل المشاهد اللي شفتها بحياتي: شروق الشمس فوق بحيرة طبريا.

#tiberias #طبريا #بحر_الجليل #nofilterneeded
translated: One of the most beautiful scenes my eyes have felt: sunrise for the Tiberias Lake. I will definitely never forget the feeling of cold breeze and warm water on my feet. I will never forget the feeling of nostalgia that something from our hearts is true.

img_description:
[人在以色列。暴走曠野]
這是頭一次見識曠野路。由加利利湖邊五餅二魚堂上八福山，再到迦百農，全用走的。路程不遠，但在38度高溫並且烈日高照下，沒有遮擋地走著……唯一能做的就是哼著歌來走畢這段路：「主能帶領我經過曠野路，我只要跟隨主腳步……」 經此一行，多少能想像耶穌和祂的門徒體能有多好。為福音，祂們去得好盡！*O* 「耶穌走遍各城各鄉，在會堂裏教訓人，宣講天國的福音，又醫治各樣的病症。」(馬太福音9章35節)

img_description:
The Sea of Galilee in the city of #Tiberias, #Israel 
The Sea holds importance in terms of #religion and #history because it is at this very place where #Jesus walked on water. 
Tiberias is a small city but full of #life with a lot of #restaurants and a bustling #fleamarket. The feeling you get here is akin to any small coastal city. 
While in Tiberias, don't forget to visit two restaurants - 
Decks for yummy continental food and Pagoda for Chinese fare. 
The city is one of contrasts, while this sea sees a lot of religious tourists, the piece of land jutting out on the right side of this photo had a raging #party on until the wee hours of the night!

img_description:
Caesarea is a Old City in Israel located mid-way between Tel Aviv and Haifa. The town was built by Herod the Great about 25-13 BCE as the port city Caesarea Maritima.

The Judaean Port of Caesarea had no reliable source of fresh water when construction. King Herod commissioned a raised aqueduct to deliver water from the springs. Today, the most impressive part of Herodian aqueduct can be seen on the beach of Caesarea, north of the ancient city.

#Israel #Caesarea #Oldcity #Seaport #Aqueduct #Ancient #Traveling

img_description:
A bunch of snaps and only a couple of shots I was able to get from our Saturday road trip to the northern part of #Jordan before our car broke down and we ended up stranded for a couple of hours. During this time, at least a hundred cards passed by and not one, not one, stopped to ask if we needed any assistance, except for a gentleman, Majed Al Rousan, that parked his car 3 times whenever he drove past us to offer help. He hooked us up with Um Qais locals that helped us out.

The car broke down after we have filled it up with fuel at one of the nearby Total gas stations, apparently, as per the locals, no one fills up from that gas station for a good reason, at least that's what they say.

In the snap is the view from Um Qais overlooking the Sea of #Galilee (a.k.a. Lake Tiberias), #Tiberias (طبريةu200e), The Yarmouk River and the #Golan Heights.

#ShareYourJordan #Jordan #Palestine #Travel

Audio: @47Soul - Dabeekeh

img_description: The Pontius Pilatus Stone in #nationalpark of #cesarea is the name given to a damaged block (82 cm x 65 cm) of carved limestone with a partially intact inscription attributed to, and mentioning, #PontiusPilate, a prefect of the #Roman province of Judaea from AD 26–36. It was discovered at the #archaeological site of #Cesarea Maritima in 1961. The artifact is particularly significant because it is the only widely accepted #archaeological find, to date, of an authentic 1st-century #Romaninscription mentioning the name Pontius Pilatus". The limestone block was discovered in June 1961 by Italian archaeologists led by Dr. Antonio Frova while #excavating in the area of an #ancienttheatre built by decree of #HerodtheGreat around 22-10 BC

img_description: Yesterday was the grand finale for my visit to Israel (went home this morning). I joined a tour that took us all the way to the Lebanese border in North, and back to Jerusalem/Tel Aviv in 12 hours. On the way we stopped at Caesarea, a city built by King Herod 2000 years ago, to honour the Roman emperor Caesar Augustus. Caesarea was used as the administrative center for the Roman province Judea. The city had its own port, roman theater (3000 seats), hippodrome (10000 seats) and a huge Palace for King Herod. On the picture you can see parts of the palace, and the hippodrome stretching along the beach. We also paid visit to the Bahai Gardens in Haifa, Rosh Hanikra and the Crusader Fortress in Acre. A bit hectic, but all in all a great finale. One last thing I would like to mention is the warmth and hospitality of the Israeli people, they were really something else. Great country, and great people. #caesarea #kingherod #Israel

img_description:
Pilgrims entering the Church of the Holy Sepulchre where they terminate the stations of the Via Dolorosa. Each station represents a place where Christ fell down whilst carryinf the cross to his cruxifiction. This trail runs through through Jerusalem's old city and many follow the stations in order, following Christ's exact footsteps.
This church was built on the place where Christ was crucified, also known as 'calvary' and where His tomb was found empty. 
This is considered one of the most crucial pilgrimage sites for Christians.

img_description:
Why do we embark upon pilgrimage? 
Despite being an important aspect of Christian traditions, pilgrimage has been an integral part of the lives of the forefathers of Christianity. It offers us the chance to connect with the prophets who themselves had an extremely important and intimate relationship with God. It guides us on a spiritual journey and forces us to witness the, often isolated and peaceful, areas where our Lord communicated with the prophets, through whom we have come to know God. 
This journey of pilgrimage definitely enables us to leave the none-stop busyness of our lives to come closer to our faith, but that does not mean pilgimage is restricted to the faithful. Travelling through the footpaths of biblical figures is undoubtedly a thrilling, historical and experience.

img_description:
The Roman Theater in Caesarea which was built during Roman Times and is still being used up to this present day.

It often hosts concerts by major Israeli and international artists, such as Shlomo Artzi, Yehudit Ravitz, Mashina, Deep Purple, Björk and others. img_description: This is the Sea of Galilee❤ ... We were supposed to visit Tiberias & the surrounding area for 2 nights but ended up staying for a few more. Everyday we would say , let's stay another day !??... Its hard to pull oneself away from it ... It holds such a draw especially with the knowledge of what has transpired here biblically. Yeshua spent a good amount of time here in the Galilee, it's a very short distance from Nazareth ... It is also one of the most beautiful parts of Israel that I have seen... I imagine that if one would spend a season alone feasting on the Holy Scriptures this would be the place to do it....Its extravagantly peaceful and there is a depth to its peace....The first day we arrived, we drank the filtered water from it and felt the blessing that came with it ?.. I felt like #Galilee ministered to us and released something wonderful . I do feel a change... #Israel #tiberias #jesus #yeshua #capernaum

img_description: 3 weeks passover vacation came to its end today. The funny thing is tho, this week I only have 2 days of classes and same thing next week (instead of my regular four). I get a feeling these last two months will pass by very quickly. Even faster than these past 6 months have gone ? I got mixed emotions about this... I'm missing Sweden, but I know I will also miss this  when I leave. The people, my friends, the surroundings, events... but who knows what will happen? Last summer I was so eager to leave Sweden, I was driving myself crazy, and didn't hesitate packing my bags and preparing my cats for leaving the country. I wouldn't be surpised if I did the same thing again, but for a different location ? #justvegan #vegantlv #tiberias #veganisthenewnormal #VeganizeEveryone #VeganRevolution #veganrunner #veganisrael #jerusalemvegans #veganistheanswer #veganism #hummusislife #hummusqueen
